column2:
A beautiful cube made up of 220 smaller boxes. Tell your own story or listen
to others. What would you like to leave the world after you’re gone?

A suite of travelling arcade machines made out of cardboard. Inside is a
computer, a monitor and a game.

In Circadial, Sleepdogs have made field recordings of Exeter, which are
spliced, stretched and warped to turn the sounds of the city into improvised
music made entirely from atmospheric sound
Magical glass buoys that speak when you get close to them.
column5: Dr Louisa Evans, Dr Rachel Turner, Jay Kerry, Daniel Marcus Clark, South Coast fishing communities, Kaleider

column2:
Find a special bench that can connect you to someone sitting on a bench
somewhere else!

Choral Cuisine will see 50 diners collectively composing a symphony whilst
sitting down to a delicious brunch.

Projected, animated prints drawn by Catherine Cartwright, of young people
from Ellen Tinkham College.

A musical installation incorporating music technology, multi-instrumental
composition, five three-foot helium balloons, and buckets upon buckets of
balls.
column5: David Sawyer (Noise Platforms) and Timothy Tate (The Sonic Balloon)

column2:
You, the audience are in control. Use your mobile phone to play Mario &
Pacman on the big screen.

column1: Come, Battle The Screenless PlayStation Game
column2:
Running around outside holding a light-up controller you must protect your
King and discover the traitor while you carefully listen to the music for clues.
A playful sound sculpture: make some moves and hear the bells chime
